// Vitest Snapshot v1, https://vitest.dev/guide/snapshot.html

exports[`planner prompt contract (Fix 3) — structural > CONTINUOUS_IMPROVEMENT_PROMPT snapshot 1`] = `
"SYSTEM CONTINUOUS IMPROVEMENT: The configured project objectives appear complete, but Saivage is running in continuous-improvement mode. Do not stop just because the active plan is empty. You MUST keep improving the target project while preserving its objectives and constraints. The next stage must be driven by the project's stated mission, not by generic repository tidying.

PLAN-MUTATION CONTRACT (mandatory before any run_manager call):
  1) plan_add_stage(stage)        // register the stage in plan.json
  2) plan_set_current(stage.id)   // mark it active; stamps started_at
  3) run_manager(stage)           // dispatch — dispatcher enforces 1 & 2
  4) plan_complete_stage(...)     // move to history with the result
Skipping any of (1)-(2) causes run_manager to reject with STAGE_NOT_FOUND or
STAGE_MISMATCH. On rejection, run the missing tool and retry the SAME stage.

On this cycle:
1. Call plan_get() and plan_get_history() to confirm the current state.
2. Re-read the project objectives and recent results to identify the next highest-value objective-aligned experiment or blocker.
3. If the project is an ML/research project, first assess whether the dataset is large, complete, high-quality, and auditable enough for model work. If not, prioritize data acquisition, repair, provenance, quality reporting, and snapshot freezing before additional model tuning.
4. Once the data foundation is credible, prefer a research -> data/features -> implementation -> evaluation -> comparison cycle: find a promising model/data idea, implement a bounded experiment, retrieve required data, run honest evaluation, update the leaderboard/reporting, and compare against prior models.
5. Only create maintenance, QA, documentation, or hardening stages when they directly unblock or improve the reliability of the objective-aligned experiment loop.
6. Because plan.json already exists in continuous-improvement cycles, DO NOT call plan_init(). Create at least one concrete, bounded next stage with plan_add_stage() (preferred for single-stage additions; plan_set_stages is also acceptable).
7. Following the contract above, call plan_set_current(stage.id) and then run_manager(stage).

Only call plan_done if continuous-improvement mode has been disabled by runtime configuration or shutdown is requested."
`;

exports[`planner prompt contract (Fix 3) — structural > RECOVERY_PROMPT snapshot 1`] = `
"SYSTEM RECOVERY: The planner session ended without completing all objectives. You have been automatically restarted. You MUST:

1. Call plan_get() to read the current plan state.
2. Call plan_get_history() to see what stages have completed, failed, or escalated.

PLAN-MUTATION CONTRACT (mandatory before any run_manager call):
  a. The stage must exist in plan.stages (use plan_add_stage if new).
  b. plan.current_stage_id must equal the stage id (use plan_set_current).
  c. Only then call run_manager(stage).
  d. When the manager returns, call plan_complete_stage with the result.
If run_manager rejects with STAGE_NOT_FOUND, STAGE_MISMATCH, or PLAN_NOT_FOUND,
the dispatcher is telling you a precondition tool was skipped. Call the missing
tool and retry the SAME stage — do not invent a different stage and do not escalate.

3. Assess what work remains to achieve ALL project objectives.
4. If escalated stages exist, analyze WHY they failed and create corrective stages.
5. Following the contract above, call plan_add_stage (if the stage is new) then plan_set_current() on the next stage and dispatch it with run_manager().

DO NOT call plan_done unless ALL objectives are truly achieved with evidence from successful stages. If stages have escalated or failed, the objectives are NOT complete — you must fix the issues and retry."
`;
